Need to double check the redshift for this system; Note that Arp 299 is mistakenly claimed to comprise IC 694 and NGC 3690 but IC 694 is a lenticular galaxy not associated with the two primary merging galaxies; our naming convention takes this into account. I quote the XMM 2-10keV X-ray coordinates of the AGNs from Ballo+ to avoid confusion with multiple APG namings but these coordinates are likely not the same exact coordinate as the Chandra source (which was not listed). Separation not based on X-ray coordinates but on work by Heckman. Garcia-Marin+2006 found that location B1 in NGC 3690 had syefert like ratios whereas Perez-Torres report the discovery of a LLAGN in IC 694 based on VLBI imaging from EVN. Alonso-Herrero+2013 presented evidence in support of the scenario in which both AGNs are deeply buried but Ptak+2015 found no evidence for more than one AGN in NuSTAR imaging. But the findings by Ptak+2015 do not necessarily disagree with the findings of the previous papers; a non-detection in IC 694 would be expected if it is indeed a LLAGN and deeply embedded.

column4: Radio Morphology+Helical Model or Structure / Quasi-periodicity
column31: Conway+ applied hydrodynamic models to the misaligned jet components in Mrk 501 and found it coud be consistent with a helical jet driven by a SMBH binary. Mrk 501 shows a roughly 79 deg twist in the PA of the jet between the pc and kpc scales. They argue this is due to the orbital motion of the binary. Villata+ argue this precession structure is due to the black hole spin axis and so the helical structure is driven by one of the black holes in the binary. Bhatta+ report a 332 day QPO in this system (that persists for up to 7 cycles) and could be driven by a SMBH (among other things)

column32: Reiger+ discuss outburst activity in 2006 and the quasi-periodicity in the context of a SMBH ; Sandrinelli+ report statistically significant quasi-periodicity using a method recommended by Vaughn+; confirms periodicity reported by Sandrinelli+2014. Zhang+ reports quasi-periodicity in 35 year light curves and variation in color.

column28: Comerford+2009b; Civano+2010; Civano+2012; Blecha+2013; Lanzuisi+2013; Wrobel+2014; Wrobel+2014
column31: Coordinates from the COSMOS naming convention. Separation from Civano+2010. Redshift from Civano+2010. Comerford argues in favor of a dual AGN in this system; Civano+10 argues that the system could be described by a recoiling SMBH or a dual AGN (Type I/Type II) with the Type I AGN recoiling. Blecha+13 finds the system can also be described using the recoiling / dual AGN+recoiling hypothesis. Ciavno+2012 uses Chandra HRC and finds only one of optical nuclei is responsible for whole X-ray unobscured; one of the nuclei is more consistent with a SF region and so they favor the GW recoil scenario rather than a dual AGN scenario; but a scenario involving a heavily obscured nucleus in the second nucleus cannot be fully ruled out. Lanzuisi+ analyzes the XMM spectrum to investigate the P-Cygni profile. Wrobel+14 finds no radio emission at the positions of the two nuclei; the NW nucleear properties are consistent with a CT AGN; they argue that CID-42 is either a dual AGN or a Type II CT AGN and a recoiling AGN where the recoiling AGN was ejected due to a triple SMBH interaction. NO ONE MENTIONS THE COORDINATES FOR DISTINCT NUCLEI. COORDINATES ARE FOR THE SYSTEM AS FAR BRIGHTNESS MEASUREMENTS; THESE ARE NOT FOR DISTINCT NUCLEI YET.

Sandrinelli+2018 also find statistically significant periodicity shortly after Tavani+ but I am not sure if they are using the latest data like Tavani+. CHECK. Cavaliere+ developed a model to describe dynamic events in blazars and specifically BL LACs; they show their model can procide a simple explanation for the recurrent but non-linear pattern of peaks and troughs in the light curves of PG 1553+113. Munar-Androver shows full view of fifth repetition of pattern again confirming repetition of the main peak as well as the lower intensity peaks before and after the dominant maxima. Caproni+ identify 7 jet components that recede ballistically from the core and their ejection is roughly coincident with previous gamma ray flares. They find that the jet prcesses with a period roughly equivalent with that derived via quasi-periodicities.

column28: Graham+2015a ; D'Orazio+2015 ; Charisi+2015 ; Kun+2015 ; Jun+2015 ; Mohan+2016 ; Liu+2018 ; Kovacevic+2019
column30: https://doi.org/10.1038/nature14143 ; https://doi:10.1093/mnras/stv1457 ; https://doi:10.1093/mnrasl/slv111 ; https://doi:10.1093/mnras/stv2049 ; https://doi:10.1088/2041-8205/814/1/L12 ; https://doi:10.1093/mnras/stw2154 ; https://doi:10.3847/2041-8213/aac2ed ; https://doi:10.3847/1538-4357/aaf731
column31: Graham+2015 identified based on optical variability in CRTS. Physical separation is an upper limit. D'Orazio+2015 argue that the period is likely smaller by a factor of 3-8 times and could therefore be in the GW regime. Charisi+2015 search for secondary periods in the periodogram but find no secondary peaks (they state the current data would only allow the detection of a secondary peak if it was equal in amplitude to the primary peak). Charisi+2015 bring up that the false alarm probability needs to be assessed in the context of the full CRTS sample which has not yet been done (i.e. needs to account for look elsewhere effect). Kun+2015 identifies complex pc-to-kpc radio jet structures that could be compatible with the binary scenario envisaged by Graham+. Jun+2015 analyzed the 3.4 and 4.6 um light curves and revealed a time lag between the mid-IR and optical. MOhan+2016 develop a model formalism for the radio jet structure and propose an intense follow-up campaign. Kovacevic+2019 proposes a binary model in which a perturbation due to a cold spot is responsible for the result found by Liu+2018 and provides predictions on the variability for future observations. D'orazio+2017 (not cited here) develops IR model that reproduces (with some caveats) what was found by Jun+2015.
